SIMPLE: magnet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Magnet
<hw>Mag"net</hw> <pr>(m⟦acr⟧g"n⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>magnete</ets>, OF. <ets>magnete</ets>, L. <ets>magnes</ets>,
<ets>-etis</ets>, Gr. <grk>Magnh^tis li`qos</grk> a magnet, metal that
looked like silver, prop., Magnesian stone, fr. Gr.
<grk>Magnhsi`a</grk>, a country in Thessaly. Cf. <er>Magnesia</er>,
<er>Manganese</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The loadstone; a species of
iron ore (the ferrosoferric or magnetic ore, <chform>Fe3O4</chform>)
which has the property of attracting iron and some of its ores, and,
when freely suspended, of pointing to the poles; -- called also
<altname>natural magnet</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dinocrates began to make the arched roof of the temple of
Arsino⟦eum⟧ all of <qex>magnet</qex>, or this loadstone.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two <qex>magnets</qex>, heaven and earth, allure to bliss,⟦br⟧
The larger loadstone that, the nearer this.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A bar or mass of steel or iron
to which the peculiar properties of the loadstone have been imparted; --
called, in distinction from the loadstone, an <altname>artificial
magnet</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ An artificial magnet, produced by the action of an
electrical current, is called an
<stype>electro-magnet</stype>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Field magnet</b></col> <fld>(Physics & Elec.)</fld>,
<cd>a magnet used for producing and maintaining a magnetic field; --
used especially of the stationary or exciting magnet of a dynamo or
electromotor in distinction from that of the moving portion or
armature.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Magnetic</ent>⟦br⟧
